Intro

  1. Spam is a data set collected at Hewlett-Packard Labs, that classifies 4601 e-mails as spam or non-spam. In addition to this class label there are 57 variables indicating the frequency of certain words and characters in the e-mail.Questions about the data:
  • Are there certain words that spam emails are more likely to contain?
  • Whats the best way to block spam emails without filtering out non-spams?

  1. The mean of mail is 0.16717 for nonspam and 0.3505074 for spam. The mean of you is 1.2703407 for nonspam and 2.2645394 for spam. The mean of will is 0.5363235 for nonspam and 0.5499724 for spam.

  2. Explore your data with a minimum of 2 graphs.

spam2 <- data.frame(spam$mail, spam$you, spam$will, spam$your, spam$type, spam$our)
plot(spam2)

spam3 <- melt(spam2, id.vars = "spam.type")
ggplot(data=spam3, aes(spam.type, value, fill=variable)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge")

Conclusion

Emails that contain word mail, you, will, and our have a higher possibility of being spams.
